The equivalent annual cost (EAC) refers to the method of comparing two assets or projects that have different lifespans. In the case of this problem, we will compare how much it costs the firm if they use an incandescent lightbulb as opposed to an LED bulb. 

To solve for the equivalent annual cost, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equivalent annual cost}&=\dfrac{\text{Net present value}}{\text{Annuity factor}}
\end{aligned}$$

For the **LED light bulb**:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Watts per hour}&=\dfrac{7 \text{W}}{40,000}\\[15 pt]
&=0.000175\text{W}
\end{aligned}$$

The LED light bulb consumes $0.000175$ Watts per hour.

Now, to solve for the net present value, we will use this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=(\text{Annual cost} \times \text{Annuity factor})+\text{Initial price}
\end{aligned}$$
